            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1422518695,
            "creation_date": 1422518695,
            "body": "<p>At the moment (version 2.1) this is not possible. JMX only instruments Loggers that are in the configuration.<\/p>\n\n<p>Without JMX, you can do something like mentioned here:\n<a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/23434252/programmatically-change-log-level-in-log4j2\">Programmatically change log level in Log4j2<\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>But this also only works for loggers that are named in the configuration...<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 28209704,
            "question_id": 28117142,
            "last_edit_date": 1495540781
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/e45dd81d0238dfb6d9a9adcf3dcf12f7?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 2680559,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 2317829,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/2317829/eebbesen",
                "reputation": 5155,
                "display_name": "eebbesen",
                "accept_rate": 76
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 0,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1462310791,
            "creation_date": 1462310791,
            "body": "<p>Have you tried remotely editing the Log4j configuration as outlined in the Client GUI section <a href=\"https://logging.apache.org/log4j/2.0/manual/jmx.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">here<\/a>?<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>Clicking the \"Reconfigure with XML below\" button will send the configuration text to the remote application where it will be used to reconfigure Log4j on the fly. This will not overwrite any configuration file. Reconfiguring with text from the editor happens in memory only and the text is not permanently stored anywhere.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n",
            "answer_id": 37014651,
            "question_id": 28117142
        }
